Because you let all the bitter old bastards call the shots.  You need to vote this year like your life depends upon on it, because now it really does.  Your apathy, and dare I say it…laziness, will bring you so much harm.</div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/yEMHiZ3</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Thelrishlnquistion]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>Audio please</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/n5aGvlZ</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/Ebo1Luj.gif" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/n5aGvlZ</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[SuperbainK]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>I see said the blind man .....</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/xxTYUP6</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/UPE0trn.png" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/xxTYUP6</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[blank666man]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>Really melts the heart.</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/TIOv87v</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/l1SkhqR.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>In London, there's a woman who goes every day on the subway and sits on the dock just to listen to the announcement recorded by her husband in 1950.
Margaret McCollum after the death of her Oswald Laurence sits on the bench waiting to hear this recording that became one of London's most famous "Mind the gap" (attention to the space between the train and the dock). In 2003, Oswald died leaving a huge void in Margaret's heart. So Margaret found a way to feel his presence closest.
But from the day after more than half a century, this voice was replaced by an empty electronic recording. Out of distress, Margaret asked this cassette tape to the London subway transport company to continue listening to her husband's voice at home.
But, knowing the moving history, the company decided to restore the announcement at the only stop near the house where the woman lives, specifically at the Embankment stop of the Northern Line, where all passengers can listen today Oswald Laurence's voice and think that eternal love exists.
Wonderful gesture by the authorities</div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/TIOv87v</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[randomposta]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>Let me slide your cheeks apart and gently insert my soup</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/NUpzKV2</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/nlqi8oG.gif" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Good ol Buffalo Chicken Chowder.  A hearty, slightly spicy bowl of silky comfort</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/spYDQYr.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Ok, before anyone asks...

Start by making a gorgonzola cream sauce.  Reduce some heavy whip by 1/4 and add enough gorg to make it good and skunky (that'll even out later).  Pinch of pepper and set aside.
Saute onion, celery, carrot and red pepper.  Add garlic.  Add chicken or veggie broth.  Add some diced Yukon gold potatoes and boil until fork tender.  Add the chicken I forgot to mention I diced, seasoned, and seared earlier.  Add the gorg sauce to the broth and veg, then add enough roux to thicken it to your liking.  The best part comes when you add a shitload of your favorite hot sauce... Frank's works great but get crazy with it.  Top with a little diced celery for crunch and some more gorg to give it that hot wing experience.  This one is a banger, guys.

